text:
Hi, I offered the math tutoring, just giving you a way to contact me, tweeted... sorta, at you, t's from a shrimp, but still me. (new account)

As I said, You are not dumb, somewhere along the lines someone simply explained things *wrong*.

I mentioned when you were at a point where you could divide or add, that if you had the option of giving me half of your money when you have little money, or more money, which would you rather do?  You want to give me as little as possible, so that you can buy strawberries and salmon, so, before getting a bunch of money (adding) you want to split your money with me (divide by 2).  Example being you have $52, you will also get $50 from a shrimp, would you rather give me $26 (52/2) or  (52+50)/2 = $51?  You would give me the $26, you need your sweet sweet Strawberry Shrimp funds!

Same goes with multiplication (leaving out fractions).  If you have the same $52, and I offer to double your money, and another shrimp offers you $50 at the same time, should you go (52x2) + 50 = $154, or should you take the Shrimps money first, then have me double it ($50 + $52)x2 = $204.  Again, you would take the money first, so that I have to double as much as possible.

To convert it to Tower math
        50
52   x2

It's slightly difficult to explain just via text, it's clearer when you can ask questions and verify you have it at every point along the way, but simple text YT explanations are the best I have right now.

Bottom line is:

For you to state "I have two hands and ten fingers"
Someone had to give you a process of figuring it out.
Step 1: To know you have two hands and ten fingers, someone first had to tell you what 'hands' are. 
Step 2: Then someone had to explain what a number is "If you can only see the single object, that is the number 1"
Step 3: Then they had to explain that if you have one 'thing' here and another 'one thing' there, if you bring them together, that is two, or twice of one.
Step 4: Then you learn what the wiggly things on your hands are, your fingers.
Step 5: Then you look back on your knowledge, spread your fingers apart, have someone point at one wiggly finger, then at another wiggly finger and ask "can you tell me how many fingers you have that I pointed at?"
Step 6: Then once you remember the answer is "two" and you respond with "two", they need to teach you how to add 2 + 1 and tell you what the answer is.
This process will have to repeat for every single number between 1 - 10 for you to be able to say you have "two hands and ten fingers".

You can't skip any of those steps to be able to answer the question.  All of the steps are small, all of them seem insignificant when looked at in that block of tasks I listed, but each one is vital to the concept of addition (and knowing what hands and fingers are).

If someone taught you the wrong method at any point during that process, you will get the wrong answer.  It does not matter if you are following the process they told you to do because they taught you the wrong process.  The same applies if you did not understand one small piece of the steps involved in figuring out how many hands and fingers you have, no matter how smart or dumb you are, you will not, unless by sheer luck, be able to give the right answer.

Life is a series of un-numbered processes, you have to be able to use knowledge you have to know what you know, then you need to be taught the rest.  If you know English, can spell English words and someone says "what does house mean?" you would not be able to answer that if you had no clue what a house is.  Be patient with yourself and be willing to ask questions and find people who are not dicks to answer those questions.
